content.description: A face climb on incut crimps.
content.protection: Fixed Anchors. I believe the first anchor is somewhat high.
content.location: Right of the left leaning dihedral crack.

content.description: It is more of a layback than a jam crack.
content.protection: This crack has great cam placements. Up to #4 BD cams. Tree for anchor. The top of the route has bad rock quality, you are not really climbing at this point because you are at a ledge, so walk around and up to the big tree above the cliff. The rock quality does not really detract from the climbs quality because the route is over at that point but be careful.
content.location: Obvious, largest, jagged, crack on the right side of the cliff but just left of an arete.

content.description: A small north facing wall along the Shenandoah River just upstream of the 340 bridge, in West Virginia. It is often shaded, requires a unique approach, and you must be aware of water levels before going.
